<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1436,1190,1365]" lastBlockId="5.[151,1435,151,212]" lastPageId="5" lastPageNumber="68" pageId="4" pageNumber="67">
Mean body length (mm) 
<number box="[611,624,1342,1364]" pageId="4" pageNumber="67" value="6.0">6</number>
7,5 6,8 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,299,1959,1983]" pageId="4" pageNumber="67">Ecology.</emphasis>
Nymphs of the new species were collected in four different sites in strong current of streams and riffles of rivers with cobble substrates. Streams ranged in width from 
<quantity box="[898,940,1994,2018]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.0" pageId="4" pageNumber="67" unit="m" value="4.0">4 m</quantity>
(Berbeg) to 
<quantity box="[1081,1137,1994,2018]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="4" pageNumber="67" unit="m" value="10.0">10 m</quantity>
(Ennour), and water depth not exceeding 
<quantity box="[320,393,151,175]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.5" pageId="5" pageNumber="68" unit="cm" value="65.0">65 cm</quantity>
at all collecting sites. The very low mineralization of water (&lt;
<number box="[1128,1179,151,175]" pageId="5" pageNumber="68" value="0.15">0.15</number>
<collectionCode box="[1189,1242,151,175]" httpUri="http://grbio.org/cool/5mg9-yyc1" name="Portland State University, Vertebrate Biology Museum" pageId="5" pageNumber="68">PSU</collectionCode>
) can explain the absence of the new species in the other streams of Northern 
<collectingCountry box="[825,908,188,212]" name="Tunisia" pageId="5" pageNumber="68">Tunisia</collectingCountry>
which are more mineralized.
</paragraph>
